h3. Issue Summary
 * Adding a large number of files (eg. +3000) to a repository's Downloads section causes an intermittent issue on the UI, not loading the files.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Add a large number of files to the repository's downloads section (eg. +3000);
 # Try to view them through the repository's Downloads section on the UI;

h3. Expected Results
 * The UI will consistently load the files;

h3. Actual Results
 * Intermittently, the UI fails to load the files;

h3. Workaround

As a workaround, it is possible to fetch the files through the REST API:
{panel}
[Repository Downloads - GET|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/downloads]
{panel}
You can also get a specific file from your downloads section:
{panel}
[Repository Downloads Files - GET|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/downloads/%7Bfilename%7D#get]
{panel}
Or it is also possible to delete old files through the API, reducing the number of files and allowing the UI to properly load:
{panel}
[Repository Downloads - DELETE|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/downloads/%7Bfilename%7D]
{panel}

h3. Issue Summary
 * Responses from the *Pipelines* endpoint returns an invalid URL for both *self* and *steps* fields which can't be accessed with regular *<username:apppassword>* authorization header;
 * 
{code:java}
"links": {
        "self": {
          "href": "https://bitbucket-pipelines.prod.public.atl-paas.net//rest/1.0/accounts/{workspace_uuid}/repositories/{repo_uuid}/pipelines/{build_uuid}"
        },
        "steps": {
          "href": "https://bitbucket-pipelines.prod.public.atl-paas.net//rest/1.0/accounts/{workspace_uuid}/repositories/{repo_uuid}/pipelines/{build_uuid}/steps"
        }
      } {code}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Make an API call to the *Pipelines* endpoint for any repository
 # In the results, you will see a *Links* object with two URLs: *self* and *steps;*
 # Try to make a GET request to that URL;

h3. Expected Results

Results should use the actual *api.bitbucket.org* domain, making it possible to fetch results from these URLs;
h3. Actual Results

Fetching the build and the steps from these URLs fail with authorization error:
{code:java}
{
  "error": {
    "message": "Unauthorized",
    "detail": "No authorization provider header specified.",
    "data": {
      "key": "rest-service.rest-service.unauthorized",
      "arguments": {}
    }
  }
} {code}
h3. Workaround

Directly fetch the build and steps from our API sub-domain;
{code:java}
/2.0/repositories/{workspace}/{repo_slug}/pipelines/{pipeline_uuid} {code}
and
{code:java}
/2.0/repositories/{workspace}/{repo_slug}/pipelines/{pipeline_uuid}/steps/ {code}

h3. Issue Summary
The following API endpoint requires a "/" at the end of any api request:
{panel}
https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/pipelines/#get
{panel}

Example:
{code}
curl -u 'username:password' https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspaceID>/<repoSlug>/pipelines
{code}
Will throw a 404:
{code}
"type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "Resource not found",
    "detail": "There is no API hosted at this URL.\n\nFor information about our API's, please refer to the documentation at: https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/"
  }

{code}

Adding the "/" character allows this request to work just fine though, like this:
{code}
curl -u 'username:password' https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspaceID>/<repoSlug>/pipelines/
{code}

This is inconsistent with other API endpoints such as https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/issues for example.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Perform an API request using the following URL:
{code}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspaceID>/<repoSlug>/pipelines
{code}

h3. Expected Results
Pipelines endpoint works with either the "/" or without it.

h3. Actual Results
Pipelines throws a 404 when performing requests to this endpoint when not using a "/" at the end of the URL

h3. Workaround
Add a "/" at the end of the Pipelines API URL.

As per [this documentation|https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/run-docker-commands-in-bitbucket-pipelines/], currently, it is not possible to mount volumes outside $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR.

Bitbucket Pipeline throws the following error if the build tries to mount a volume outside $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR. 
{code:java}
ERROR: failed to build: failed to create 'creator' container: Error response from daemon: authorization denied by plugin pipelines: -v only supports $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR and its subdirectories
{code}
This feature request is to allow mounting volumes outside $BITBUCKET_CLONE_DIR in Bitbucket pipelines.

